[2026-03-24 08:58:24.811] INFO -- [TaskAgentRuntimeService] 🎯 Planning function result: {:success=>true, :plan=>{"goal"=>"Monitor technology news and create a daily summary focused on AI, cloud computing, and cybersecurity developments.", "steps"=>[{"id"=>"step_1", "notes"=>"Fetched 10 AI-related articles (en). Sources include Bloomberg, Livemint, MarketScreener, Baltimore News/WJLA, Times of India, BNN Bloomberg, CP24, The Canberra Times. Themes: US AI policy blueprint; Meta hiring Dreamer team; OpenAI ad sales leadership hire; US-China AI competitiveness warnings; defense AI collaboration (Saab–Cohere); workforce AI skills gap. Dedupes noted: same AI policy piece (Baltimore News & WJLA); same Saab–Cohere story (BNN Bloomberg & CP24); same Dreamer hire (Bloomberg & Livemint).", "order"=>1, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:28:39Z", "description"=>"Fetch latest AI news articles using the news API", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:31:43Z"}, {"id"=>"step_2", "notes"=>"Fetched cloud computing news across general and provider-specific queries (cloud computing, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud). Within the last 24h, notable items include: Google Cloud agentic AI security strategy (SiliconANGLE, 2026-03-23), Azure Monitor-themed callback phishing campaign (TechRadar, 2026-03-23), and Australian government data centre expectations raising investment concerns (AFR, 2026-03-23). Many AWS/Nvidia deal items are older (Mar 19–20) and will be excluded in the 24h filter. Rate-limit hit on 'data center' query; sufficient coverage achieved without it.", "order"=>2, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:32:28Z", "description"=>"Fetch latest cloud computing news articles using the news API", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:37:09Z"}, {"id"=>"step_3", "notes"=>"Fetched latest cybersecurity coverage via 3 queries: (1) `cybersecurity` (10 items), (2) `data breach` (10 items), (3) `ransomware` (10 items). Highlights within the past 24h: (a) Crunchyroll alleged data breach/intrusion claims under investigation — covered by CNET (2026-03-23), GamesRadar+ (2026-03-23), Screen Rant (2026-03-23), MobileSyrup (2026-03-23), Times Now (2026-03-23). (b) RSAC 2026 award announcements: VikingCloud (compliance/CCS Advantage), Synack (AI-powered pentesting, PTaaS), Nokod (no-code security) — PR Newswire UK (2026-03-23). (c) Analysis/opinions: TNW argues passwordless adoption is still years away (2026-03-23). (d) SCMP reports on wartime targeting of surveillance camera networks in Iran, underscoring systemic risks (2026-03-23). Additional items (within 24h window but lower priority): Worcester (MA) relaunches ALERTWorcester after 2025 CodeRED breach (MassLive, 2026-03-23). Older-but-relevant items from `ransomware` query (outside 24h): CISA adds actively exploited Zimbra/SharePoint flaws; Cisco FMC zero-day abused by Interlock; BYOVD EDR killers analysis (The Hacker News, Mar 19). Dedupes: TRAI/AI-in-telecom story appears across The Economic Times & Devdiscourse; Seeking Alpha published two near-duplicate ‘sector winners’ pieces touching on cybersecurity stocks.", "order"=>3, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:38:04Z", "description"=>"Fetch latest cybersecurity news articles using the news API", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:45:15Z"}, {"id"=>"step_4", "notes"=>"Shortlists (filtered to ~past 24h and deduped):\n\nAI\n1) US AI policy/governance blueprint gaining traction — coverage across Bloomberg; Baltimore News/WJLA; Times of India (Mar 23, 2026). 2) Meta’s “Dreamer” team build-out/hiring — Bloomberg; Livemint (Mar 23, 2026). 3) Defense AI collaboration: Saab partners with Cohere to accelerate mission applications — BNN Bloomberg; CP24 (Mar 23, 2026). 4) US–China AI competitiveness warnings — multiple outlets (Mar 23, 2026). 5) Ongoing AI workforce skills gap reports — The Canberra Times and others (Mar 23, 2026).\n\nCloud computing\n1) Google Cloud outlines “agentic AI security” posture — SiliconANGLE (Mar 23, 2026). 2) Azure Monitor-themed callback phishing mimicking Microsoft alerts — TechRadar Pro (Mar 23, 2026). 3) Australia’s evolving data centre expectations/regulatory scrutiny and investment implications — AFR (Mar 23, 2026).\n\nCybersecurity\n1) Crunchyroll alleged breach under investigation; threat actor claims ~100GB exfil incl. tickets/PII — CNET; GamesRadar+; Screen Rant; MobileSyrup (Mar 23, 2026). 2) RSAC 2026 Global InfoSec awards spotlight AI-powered security, compliance, and no‑code security — VikingCloud; Synack; Nokod press releases (PR Newswire UK, Mar 23, 2026). 3) Passwordless future still years away, per industry analysis — The Next Web (Mar 23, 2026). 4) Wartime targeting of nationwide surveillance camera networks reported in Iran case — SCMP (Mar 23, 2026). [Notes: Excluded borderline/older items: Times Now Crunchyroll piece ~07:13Z (just outside 24h window); The Hacker News BYOVD/CISA items are Mar 19. Local Worcester alert system relaunch retained as tertiary note only.]", "order"=>4, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:46:43Z", "description"=>"Aggregate and deduplicate results; filter to items from the past 24 hours; shortlist the top 3–5 developments per category based on relevance and cross-source mentions", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:49:28Z"}, {"id"=>"step_5", "notes"=>"Verification outcomes:\n\nCybersecurity\n- Crunchyroll alleged breach: Multi-source coverage (CNET; GamesRadar+; Screen Rant; MobileSyrup, all Mar 23). Common facts: Crunchyroll acknowledges awareness and is investigating. Claims of ~100GB exfiltration and possible credit card exposure are asserted by third parties and remain unverified. Some outlets mention linkage to a separate Telus Digital incident; this is not confirmed by Crunchyroll. Treat sensitive-data claims as unconfirmed.\n- RSAC 2026 awards (VikingCloud, Synack, Nokod): Vendor press releases (PR Newswire UK, Mar 23). Considered vendor-sourced claims; no material disputes found. Classify as announcements/marketing rather than independent evaluations.\n- Passwordless future article (TNW): Opinion/analysis citing industry surveys; not an event. No contradictory reporting noted, but treat as interpretation rather than hard fact.\n- Iran surveillance cameras story (SCMP): Single-source wartime account. Lacks independent corroboration in our set. Mark as single-source; treat cautiously.\n\nCloud\n- Google Cloud “agentic AI security” strategy (SiliconANGLE): Coverage of vendor positioning. Single-source media analysis; acceptable as strategic update; not a security incident.\n- Azure Monitor-themed callback phishing (TechRadar Pro): Single-source report of an observed phishing trend; no direct corroboration identified in our set; plausible given prior patterns, but treat as single-source.\n- Australia data centre oversight/investment implications (AFR): Single-source business/regulatory coverage; no dispute noted.\n\nAI\n- US AI policy blueprint: Reported across multiple outlets (e.g., Baltimore News/WJLA; Times of India; Bloomberg). Multi-source; facts align (policy details and stakeholder reactions).\n- Meta “Dreamer” team hiring: Multi-source (Bloomberg; Livemint). Consistent details on scope/hiring focus.\n- Saab–Cohere defense AI collaboration: Multi-source (BNN Bloomberg; CP24). No discrepancies.\n- US–China AI competitiveness warnings: Multi-outlet commentary; consistent high-level claims; details vary by source emphasis.\n- AI workforce skills gap: Reported by The Canberra Times and others; analysis/survey-based rather than hard events.", "order"=>5, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:50:52Z", "description"=>"Cross-verify key claims across multiple sources; separate confirmed facts from opinions; note any discrepancies", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:53:15Z"}, {"id"=>"step_6", "notes"=>"Daily Tech News Summary — Focus on AI, Cloud, and Cybersecurity (past 24 hours)\n\nAI\n- US AI policy blueprint gains momentum\n  • What happened: Multiple outlets detail a U.S. AI policy/governance blueprint and stakeholder reactions.\n  • Why it matters: Signals regulatory direction on AI safety, innovation, and national competitiveness.\n  • Potential impact: Could shape compliance obligations, public-sector AI adoption, and funding priorities.\n  • Sources: Baltimore News/WJLA; Times of India; Bloomberg — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Meta builds out “Dreamer” team\n  • What happened: Reporting indicates Meta is expanding a new “Dreamer” team focused on advanced AI.\n  • Why it matters: Highlights Big Tech’s continued investment in frontier AI talent and models.\n  • Potential impact: Competitive pressure on AI hiring; potential new consumer/creator AI experiences.\n  • Sources: Bloomberg; Livemint — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Saab partners with Cohere on defense AI\n  • What happened: Defense contractor Saab collaborates with Cohere to accelerate mission AI applications.\n  • Why it matters: Reflects deepening ties between defense and foundation model providers.\n  • Potential impact: Faster deployment of AI-enabled C2/ISR workflows; procurement and security scrutiny.\n  • Sources: BNN Bloomberg; CP24 — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- US–China AI competitiveness warnings\n  • What happened: Analysts and officials flag intensifying AI race dynamics between the U.S. and China.\n  • Why it matters: Frames geopolitics around compute, talent, and supply chains.\n  • Potential impact: Export controls, R&D incentives, and partnership strategies may shift.\n  • Sources: Multiple outlets — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- AI workforce skills gap persists\n  • What happened: New reporting underscores persistent AI skills shortages in the labor market.\n  • Why it matters: Talent scarcity remains a primary bottleneck for enterprise AI adoption.\n  • Potential impact: Increased training budgets, partnerships with edtech, and hiring competition.\n  • Sources: The Canberra Times (and others) — Mar 23, 2026.\n\nCloud computing\n- Google Cloud outlines “agentic AI security” approach\n  • What happened: Coverage describes Google Cloud’s strategy to embed agentic AI into security operations.\n  • Why it matters: Points to cloud providers productizing autonomous/assistive security capabilities.\n  • Potential impact: New cloud-native security features; SOC workflows may increasingly rely on AI agents.\n  • Source: SiliconANGLE — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Azure Monitor-themed callback phishing campaign\n  • What happened: Reported phishing lures impersonate Azure Monitor alerting to trigger callback fraud.\n  • Why it matters: Highlights attacker pivot to operational tooling lookalikes, raising user risk.\n  • Potential impact: Need for user education and technical controls against callback/social engineering.\n  • Source: TechRadar Pro — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Australia tightens focus on data centres\n  • What happened: Reporting notes changing government expectations for data centres and investment risk.\n  • Why it matters: Regulatory clarity can shape where and how hyperscalers and enterprises invest.\n  • Potential impact: Capex allocation, facility standards, and timelines could be affected.\n  • Source: Australian Financial Review — Mar 23, 2026.\n\nCybersecurity\n- Crunchyroll investigates alleged breach\n  • What happened: Rumors of a cyberattack/data breach are under investigation; some third parties claim ~100GB of stolen data tied to a third-party provider.\n  • Why it matters: Potential exposure of customer data at a major streaming platform; highlights third‑party risk.\n  • Potential impact: If confirmed, incident response, user notifications, and regulatory scrutiny could follow; users may reset passwords as precaution.\n  • Sources: CNET; GamesRadar+; Screen Rant; MobileSyrup — Mar 23, 2026. Note: Claims about sensitive data are unverified; Crunchyroll says it is investigating.\n\n- RSAC 2026 awards spotlight AI-driven security\n  • What happened: Vendors announce Global InfoSec Awards wins (e.g., VikingCloud for compliance, Synack for AI‑powered pentesting, Nokod for no‑code security).\n  • Why it matters: Underscores market momentum around continuous, AI‑assisted security and citizen‑dev risk.\n  • Potential impact: Buyer interest in compliance automation, PTaaS, and no‑code security tooling may rise.\n  • Source: PR Newswire UK (vendor press releases) — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Passwordless future still a way off\n  • What happened: Industry analysis argues most organizations still rely heavily on passwords despite passkeys/biometrics pushes.\n  • Why it matters: Emphasizes the near‑term need for stronger credential hygiene and phishing‑resistant MFA.\n  • Potential impact: Expect continued investment in identity security, secrets management, and conditional access.\n  • Source: The Next Web — Mar 23, 2026.\n\n- Surveillance cameras as wartime targets\n  • What happened: Report details hijacking of national CCTV networks in wartime operations, raising systemic risk concerns.\n  • Why it matters: Camera ecosystems are massive, heterogenous, and often weakly secured; exploitation can have kinetic consequences.\n  • Potential impact: Accelerated demand for camera fleet hardening, segmentation, and zero‑trust edge controls.\n  • Source: South China Morning Post — Mar 23, 2026. Single‑source; treat cautiously.", "order"=>6, "status"=>"completed", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:54:05Z", "description"=>"Draft the daily summary with categorized bullet points (what happened, why it matters, potential impact) and include source citations with publication dates", "completed_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:56:39Z"}, {"id"=>"step_7", "notes"=>"Reviewing summary for balance and clarity: avoiding overstatement, flagging single-source reports and unverified claims; ensuring each item has a clear why-it-matters and potential-impact; trimming marketing hype from PR items.", "order"=>7, "status"=>"in_progress", "started_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:57:23Z", "description"=>"Review for balance, objectivity, and clarity; finalize and deliver the summary", "completed_at"=>nil}], "status"=>"in_progress", "created_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:25:54Z", "updated_at"=>"2026-03-24T07:57:23Z", "completion_summary"=>nil}, :progress_percentage=>86, :completed_steps=>6, :total_steps=>7}
